  "prompt": "What is XS3 code?",
  "response": "XS3 (also known as Excess-3 or Excess-3 code) is a method of encoding decimal digits in binary form, commonly used in early computing systems. Here are key points about XS3 code:\n\n1. Basic Characteristics:\n- It's a non-weighted binary code\n- Used for representing decimal digits (0-9)\n- Each decimal digit is represented by a 4-bit binary number\n\n2. Encoding Method:\n- Add 3 to each decimal digit before converting to binary\n- Example: Decimal 0 becomes binary 0011, Decimal 1 becomes 0100\n\n3. Representation Range:\n- Covers decimal digits from 0 to 9\n- Uses 4-bit binary representation\n\n4. Advantages:\n- Self-complementing code\n- Simplifies arithmetic operations\n- Reduces complexity in digital circuits\n\n5. Example Conversions:\n- 0 (decimal) \u2192 0011 (XS3)\n- 1 (decimal) \u2192 0100 (XS3)\n- 2 (decimal) \u2192 0101 (XS3)\n- 9 (decimal) \u2192 1100 (XS3)\n\nXS3 code was primarily used in early computing and digital systems but has limited application in modern computing.",
